            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-bark-600">Thickening or repairing turf that&rsquo;s already there? Get the reduced rate scaled to your lawn&rsquo;s condition.</p>
            <span class="mt-auto inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-moss-700">
              Open
              <svg class="ml-1 h-4 w-4 transition group-hover:translate-x-0.5" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
            </span>
          </a>
        </div>

        <h2 id="choosing-the-right-grass-type">Choosing the Right Grass Type</h2>
        <p>
          Lawn grasses split into two broad groups by climate. <strong>Cool-season grasses</strong> &mdash; Kentucky bluegrass, tall fescue, perennial ryegrass, fine fescue &mdash; thrive in the cooler climates of the Northern U.S. and the transition zone, grow most actively in spring and fall, and can go semi-dormant (brown) during peak summer heat. <strong>Warm-season grasses</strong> &mdash; Bermuda, Zoysia &mdash; thrive in the hot climates of the Southern U.S., grow most vigorously through summer heat, and go dormant (brown) once temperatures drop in winter.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <a href="/calculators/grass-seed-calculator/">Grass Seed Calculator</a>&rsquo;s grass-type dropdown covers both groups for establishing a new lawn, and the <a href="/calculators/overseeding-calculator/">Overseeding Calculator</a> covers the same species (plus winter-overseeding a dormant Bermuda lawn with ryegrass for color) for renovating existing turf. We&rsquo;re also working on a dedicated Cool-Season vs. Warm-Season Grass guide with a full climate map and species-by-species comparison &mdash; check back soon.
        </p>

        <h2 id="lawn-care-timing">Lawn Care Timing</h2>
        <p>
          Timing matters as much as rate. Cool-season grasses germinate best when seeded in <strong>late summer to early fall</strong>, when warm soil and cooling air give fast germination without the stress of summer heat on new seedlings &mdash; early spring is a secondary, less reliable window for the same species. Warm-season grasses like Bermuda and Zoysia establish best once soil has warmed in <strong>late spring to early summer</strong>, while they&rsquo;re actively growing rather than dormant. Winter-overseeding a dormant Bermuda lawn with ryegrass happens in <strong>fall</strong>, timed to when the Bermuda itself is going dormant.
        </p>
        <p>
          Just like the vegetable planting dates elsewhere on this site are built around your local frost dates, lawn seeding windows are built around your local climate and grass type rather than a single calendar date. Check our <a href="/calculators/frost-date-calculator/">Frost Date Calculator</a> for your specific last and first frost dates as a starting reference point for spring and fall seeding windows in your area.
        </p>
          </>
        )}

        {isIndoorPillar && (
          <>
        <h2 id="how-much-light-does-your-plant-need">How Much Light Does Your Plant Need?</h2>
        <p>
          Houseplants roughly split into three light categories. <strong>Low light</strong> plants (snake plant, ZZ plant, pothos) tolerate the dim conditions of a north-facing window or a spot several feet back from any window, though they still grow faster in brighter conditions. <strong>Medium light</strong> plants (most monsteras, many ferns) want bright, indirect light &mdash; close to an east or west-facing window, or a few feet back from a south-facing one, but out of direct sun. <strong>High light</strong> plants (fiddle leaf figs, succulents, cacti) want the brightest indirect light your home offers, and several hours of direct sun does most of them no harm at all.
        </p>
        <p>
          &ldquo;Bright&rdquo; and &ldquo;dim&rdquo; are subjective &mdash; Daily Light Integral (DLI) turns light into an actual number you can compare against a target range, the same way a thermometer replaces guessing whether a room feels warm.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose my-8 rounded-2xl bg-white p-6 shadow-card ring-1 ring-moss-100/60">
          <span class="text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-moss-600">Calculate it</span>
          <h3 class="mt-1 font-display text-lg font-semibold text-bark-900">Grow Light &amp; DLI Calculator</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-bark-600">Turn a light reading into Daily Light Integral, or find the right grow light wattage and hanging distance for a spot with no natural light at all.</p>
          <a
            href="/calculators/grow-light-calculator/"
            class="group mt-4 inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-moss-700"
          >
            Open the calculator
            <svg class="ml-1 h-4 w-4 transition group-hover:translate-x-0.5" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </a>
        </div>

        <p class="text-sm text-bark-500">
          We&rsquo;re also working on a dedicated &ldquo;LED vs. Fluorescent Grow Lights: Which Should You Use?&rdquo; guide for anyone supplementing natural light &mdash; check back soon.
        </p>

        <h2 id="choosing-the-right-pot-size">Choosing the Right Pot Size</h2>
        <p>
          A pot that&rsquo;s too small restricts root growth and dries out fast enough that you&rsquo;re watering constantly just to keep up. A pot that&rsquo;s too large holds more wet soil than the roots can use between waterings, which keeps the soil damp long enough to invite root rot &mdash; sizing up gradually, not jumping several sizes at once, is the safer default for most houseplants.
        </p>
        <p>
          Three signs it&rsquo;s time to repot: roots <strong>circling the drainage hole</strong> or visibly emerging from it, water <strong>running straight through</strong> the pot without the soil holding any of it (a sign the roots have displaced most of the soil), and <strong>growth slowing or stalling</strong> during the plant&rsquo;s active growing season despite otherwise normal care. Any one of these on its own is worth checking; all three together mean it&rsquo;s overdue.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose my-8 rounded-2xl bg-white p-6 shadow-card ring-1 ring-moss-100/60">
          <span class="text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-moss-600">Calculate it</span>
          <h3 class="mt-1 font-display text-lg font-semibold text-bark-900">Pot Size Calculator</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-bark-600">Convert between pot sizing conventions (inches, gallons, liters), find the recommended next size up, or look up a starting size for your plant.</p>
          <a
            href="/calculators/pot-size-calculator/"
            class="group mt-4 inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-moss-700"
          >
            Open the calculator
            <svg class="ml-1 h-4 w-4 transition group-hover:translate-x-0.5" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
          </a>
        </div>

        <h2 id="quick-reference-light-and-pot-size">Quick Reference: Light and Pot Size by Common Houseplant</h2>
        <p>
          Light needs and pot size are independent decisions, not two versions of the same choice &mdash; a plant can need bright light in a small pot, or low light in a large one. Here&rsquo;s where six common houseplants land on both:
        </p>
        <div class="not-prose my-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-[#5C4433]/15 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-moss-100 text-bark-500">
                <th scope="col" class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Plant</th>
                <th scope="col" class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Light category</th>
                <th scope="col" class="py-2 font-medium">Typical starting pot size</th>
